Beta-dispersion tests were not significant for either Bray-Curtis (p = 0.967) or Aitchison distance (p = 0.243). This reduces concern that the Aitchison PERMANOVA result was driven only by unequal group dispersion.

The effect size was small: diagnosis explained approximately 3.6% of Aitchison community variation. This is not a large separation, but it is meaningful for a heterogeneous human microbiome dataset and supports the decision to continue with cross-omics integration.

## Genus-level taxa showed nominal but not FDR-significant disease associations

The genus-level association analysis tested 39 filtered taxa across four disease comparisons, producing 156 association results. No genus-level taxa survived FDR correction.

